         <listPerson>
            <person sex="1">
               <persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n1">መኰንን፡ ወልደ፡ ሚካእል፡</persName>
               <persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n1" type="normalized">Makʷannǝn Walda Mikāʾel</persName>
               <persName><roleName type="title">bālāmbārās</roleName></persName>
                <persName><roleName type="title">rās</roleName></persName>
                <birth when="1852-05-08"><placeName ref="LOC3556Gola"></placeName>
                He was a son of <persName ref="PRS9953WaldaMi"></persName> and <persName ref="PRS9235Tananna"></persName>.
              </birth>
                <floruit>
                He was invited to the court of <persName ref="PRS7006Menilek"></persName> in <date>1865</date>. His first, common-law,
                 wife gave birth to their son <persName ref="PRS10309YelmaM"></persName>. In <date>1876</date>, he married
                 <persName ref="PRS10255Yasimma">Yašimmabet ʾAli</persName>, who gave birth to <persName ref="PRS5226haylase">Tafari</persName>.
                 In <date>1876</date> Makʷannǝn Walda Mikāʾel became <roleName type="rank">bālāmbārās</roleName> and in
                 <date>1881</date> he joined a campaign against the <persName ref="ETH1973Oromo"></persName>.
                 After the conquest of <placeName ref="LOC3786Harar"></placeName>, he was awarded the rank of
                 <roleName type="rank">daǧǧāzmāč</roleName> and became the governor of the region. In <date>1887</date>
                 Makʷannǝn Walda Mikāʾel started the imperial expansion to the east and south of
                 <placeName ref="LOC3786Harar"></placeName> and conquered the parts of <placeName ref="LOC5040Ogaden"></placeName>,
                 as well as parts of the territories of <persName ref="ETH1496Gadabu"></persName> and
                 <persName ref="ETH1728Issa"></persName>.<lb/>
                 Makʷannǝn Walda Mikāʾel had good relations with expatriates and lead Ethiopian missions abroad.In the year
                 <date>1890</date> he participated in the Ethio-Italien debates, and in <date>1895-1896</date> in the Italien war. In
                 <date>1902</date> he represented <persName ref="PRS7006Menilek"></persName> at the coronation of
                 <persName ref="PRS3673EdwardV"></persName> in <placeName ref="LOC4325London"></placeName>.
                </floruit>
                <death when="1906-03-22"><placeName ref="LOC5256Qulleb"></placeName> He died on his way to
              <placeName ref="LOC1216AddisA"></placeName>, where he travelled on the occasion of the visit of
            <persName ref="PRS6807Martini"></persName>.</death>
            </person>
